<userid>103314969777201482283</userid><user_name>Angeline Herrera<//user_name><Time>1576249395732<//Time><rating>5<//rating>< Text>
4.6 stars... Some places you need to go back to appreciate it more. Strike of death is cleanliness or sanitation but if it's not that then it may be worth another try. It took me more than 4 visits for me to write this review. I hesitated and hesitated because I didn't like their service when I initially visited this place. Then I really like their chicken essence products. Then I got to-order foods. They were good but not great.

Then finally I ate here for the very first time. It changed my attitude about this place for good. I also understand why people would drive all the way from Pasadena area to this place. Still I'm not sure about an one-hour drive. Lol

This visit we ordered the Chinese yam beef rib soup combo as well as the minced pork rice combo. They were both so good. The amount of food they give for the combo was amazing. Hence the value is incredible. It made to-go order looks silly. Also their food you really need to have it there and then. It makes such a difference!

Broth, you've had me on the 5th Visit.< /Text>

<user>105900969683156785601<//user><user_name>Nina To</user_name><Time>1567803271147<//Time><Rating>4< /Rating>< Review>
Specializes in their concentrated broth, this place is a hidden gem!  It is small though, but service is fast and wonderful. I see a lot of to-go orders too. They make the chicken essence which sounds expensive xz because it's like $10 for a coffee cup size of broth. But this is like uber concentrated chicken broth, prob equivalent to a while chicken in that tiny amount.

They sell them as gift boxes too, as Chinese people believe that these chicken essence is good for your health.  I might just come back and buy some for the holidays!

We had the braised pork rice, which comes with a small side soup. The pork was nice and fatty but tender, filled with lots of minced mustards and woodear over rice.... delicious!
Definitely seems like a place I'd stumble upon in Taiwan.</Review>

<UserId.>107668518674250212585<//UserId.>< user_name>
Michelly Calzadilla</user_name>
<time>1620611453205< /time><Rating>5< /Rating>< text>
We only had a day to spend in Yosemite and wanted to make the most of it, so glad we chose this hike. Make sure you get to the trailhead early (before 9:00 AM), because it fills up quickly and parking becomes non-existent. The stairs are tough, but there are plenty of areas to catch your breath and take it at your own pace. Almost nobody was wearing a mask. You will get very wet, like a full on shower, but don't be that one person that brings a full-on poncho. Embrace the mist, it's part of the experience. Hike all the way to Nevada Falls and you will be rewarded with spectacular views of the Yosemite Valley. It's hard and long (we took a solid 6 hours), but so worth it. Absolutely spectacular scenery. Highly recommended.</text>

['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNlS13E3wBTPo-sndpattP9JTCjnIXlPDmP3OI-=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOZ2DTbFZ-AlMEHH_Q2qHPQcOB27_FZqPO1Rw-9=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOFBvqfj6axWoG2aIwk_qhdXGnqTTvzjwlxfis9=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pics><Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
This trail goes all over Yosemite, I walked the Nevada Falls to the valley section and the scenery was amazing. It would be a slog up hill, I was coming down hill. I would walk up the Mist Trail then down the Muir Trail. The footing for the most part is groomed gravel and stairs in some places. There are many many switch backs. Up near Nevada falls the footing is natural stone and is slippery and had ice on it (at 4pm) in some places so keep your wits about you. This is a challenging trail. The scenery is absolutely amazing. If you go to Nevada falls this way its probably somewhat easier than the Mist Trail but you will miss Vernal Falls and the views from below Nevada Falls.</Text>

This is where you hook up with the quintessential Yosemite hike.  The hike to Vernal Falls is the post card experience. This trail can be very busy during peek season.  You can experience much more if you plan your timing early in the morning or out of season.  The falls have a lot less flow in late summer and fall but it is always beautiful.<//Text>

<text>Service Repair: As a retired Customer Service Manager I really look at Service Technicians when they come to my home.  First, I see the vehicle they come in.  How does the vehicle look is my first thought.  Does it appear to be clean and well taken care of?  Does it look like the Company keeps their logos on the vehicles in good condition, if the vehicle has logos on it?  I even look to see how they park.  Do they seem to be aware of the parking on street?  Do they park to cause the least disruption to any neighbors?  Next I notice the Technicians dress.  Does it appear that the Technician seems to take pride in his appearance?  I even notice if this work shoes/boots could use a coat of polish.  If I am his first stop of the day, does it seem like his cloths are ironed, if they needed to be ironed?  Next I notice the Technician himself.  Is he clean if my stop is the first stop?  Is he neat in his appearance?  If he has a lot of tattoos, does he seem to try to cover them up so as not to offend the customers who might be offended?   Next I listen to how the Technician talks, and how much he talks.  Does he seem to invite conversations, stop working while talking?  When engaged in conversations does he have the ability to seem friendly, yet keep the conversations on a professional level?  When working, does the Technician seem knowledgeable about the project he is working on?  If the Technician runs into a problem does he see to inform me of the issue and seek help right away?  Is the Technician neat and orderly with his tools, does he keep them handy and not spend time looking for a tool he laid down and cannot now find?    When the Technician is working, if I am standing there talking to him, is he open to sharing what he is doing and why?  Does he commutate in a manner that allows a layman to understand what he is doing?  When the Technician is done, does he leave the area, including the floor, if there was water or dirt on the floor resulting from the repair, clean?  I also notice how well the Technician explains the bill and how much time is he willing to take to make sure his customer understands everything he has done, how to read and understand the bill, and is satisfied with the work done.  On a scale of 1 to 5 with 5 being the top, your Technician rated a 5+ on his visit.</text>< Pictures>

<name>Max< /name>< text>
There are a lot of weights, machines, and features, like an indoor track, ping pong tables, and a large basketball court. For most things, there won't be a wait time, but sometimes there is. The design and atmosphere of the gym is great. The pool has a section with lanes and a section without, which is nice. The hot tub is spacious. Students can bring a guest 10 times per semester which is convenient if you want to go with a non-student. While the men's and women's locker rooms are very nice, the gender inclusive alternative is small and missing many features that are included in the men's and women's, and the single-stall with lock design can get very inconvenient if multiple people want to use it (most times it's free and unlocked when I want to use it but, but always). The option is helpful especially for trans students like myself, and is a step in the right direction (all other gyms I've attended do not have this option at all), but I hope one day for all genders to be treated equally. Hooch the cat is usually outside the gym napping and being pet by gym-goers, and it's lovely seeing them when going to the Wrec. Overall it's a good gym that I enjoy going to.<//text>

< review>
Great gym, nice facilities, love working out there. However, it would be nice if they allowed alumni to buy memberships. The WREC is so wonderful that I don't want to work out anywhere else. The other gym's in Chico suck and are overpriced. Please consider some type of alumni membership option. It would be greatly appreciated by the alumni who still live locally.< /review>

<review>Awesome place for university students to work out, super clean! And it's free for Chico state students! There is an indoor track, which is 1/4 of a mild long, there are free weights on the lower levels, with elipiycals and stationary bikes on the second floor, there is also free lockers which is super nice, the pool is outdoors, and heated, with 2 got tubs along with it, there is a huge basket ball court, and a soccor court as well. They have trainers as well, it's free if you are a Chico state student.< /review>< rate>

<name>Adrian P.Y. Blumberg< /name>< time>
1628506224371<//time>
<Rating>3< /Rating>< Text>
Way more micro management of the outside area than seemed necessary or required. Update: the manager came and found me, and called to me by name. This never, ever happens. He asked why I gave 3 stars. I informed him 5 stars don't go out often, 4 is excellent, and 3 is average. He pressed, I told him what occurred and he said he would speak to the staff. While making it a point to address the issue is admirable, fact is, I do not give out 4 stars often, and 5 stars even less. I have only been to this location twice and I was working both times. I cannot bump up a star because I was engaged. I have metrics I adhere to. If they are satisfied, then I adjust appropriately. Until then, it remains 3 stars, which means it is a solidly average bar. I have been to enough to know the difference between a 3,4, and the rare 5. My reviews reflect myself as much as the owner. I want my ratings to mean something. When my experience hits a 4 or 5, I want folks to pay attention, otherwise, being solid should be fine. I certainly feel in the spotlight, and that is never good. I wasn't looking for it.<//Text>

This is a great beer lovers hangout. (Yes they also have some wine and ciders). The owner is extremely knowledgeable and friendly. The selection is the best in Marin without a doubt. 5< /rate>
< Text>
Beer. Wonderful beer. Something something god is good because beer. - Benjamin Franklin (not verbatim)

This place is an awesome little shop and tasting room for local beers. Wow. What a place this is with a variety of beers of different styles. Stop in and pick up cans or bottles from the massive fridges.

The staff is nice and the space is clean and warm to sit with friends or alone.

I just wish they had snacks to eat because it's easy to get wasted on an empty stomach after work.

PS the picture is blurry I know, but that's usually the view you'll have here.<//Text>

<Rate>5< /Rate>< Text>
My daughter chose this place for our dinner tonight.  We went in hungry and left stuffed!  Delicious food with large entree portions.

Started out with the abalone calamari and it was delicious.  The seared ahi wontons were yummy.  These were appetizers/pupus.  Both great choices.

The entrees were absolutely delicious and the portions HUGE!  I had the Ahi Tuna Bowl and it came in a large bowl, along with my daughters Kingston crab curry. What a unique flavor- Yum!  My son had the jerk pork.  Perfectly cooked with the right texture.  The Kalbi ribs my other daughter had was flavorful and very soft, not hard like some places.  To top off the entrees, my wife had the Fish soup and it was HUGE!  I swear after we passed the bowl around with all the members of the family, there was still some leftover that would probably last another meals worth.

We finished off the evening with the most awesome pies.  Do not leave without having a piece of the lilikoi Rita Pie on a Graham cracker.  That pretty much finished off my evening to the last piece.  Our waiter Marcus was very attentive and polite and the ladies that helped out were polite as well.  We're coming back again here for sure in the future!!< /Text>

<UserId.>105672709365552556865<//UserId.><Name>A N<//Name><date>1507068486576</date>< rating>
5< /rating>
< text>
My husband and I came here for a late lunch because I found online that their menu would work for my food sensitivities. It was Happy Hour so the place became full shortly after we got there but it's a very cozy place so it wasn't a big deal. They keep the doors open so the breeze felt amazing. My husband ordered the wings off the HH menu, they were only ~$6 for like 10. I was impressed by the quantity and the waitress actually came by to let me know they were GF which meant I could have them too! That made me really happy and the wings were seriously delicious, I never eat or like wings! Husband also got the bao sliders & egg rolls which were much smaller portions but he liked them. I ordered the calamari steak sandwich, once the waitress brought it out I realized there was a small issue but they took care of it and brought me a new one with apologies. That sandwich was some of the best seafood I've ever had! I want to eat it every day, and the gluten free bread was the best I've ever had. I got mine without the pesto since it has dairy in it but I didn't feel it was missing a thing. I also got the Hula sauce on the side as recommended by the waitress. I would buy that stuff by the pound if I could! It was so amazing with my sweet potato fries. I have saved this place in my Maps and cannot wait to go back!<//text>

<text>If you are looking for Hawaiian, then this is the obvious choice around these parts. Got the Kalbi Korean style ribs and accidentally ordering off the gluten free menu the Jawaiian Jerked style chicken which turned out to not be gluten free because the waiter asked!

<Text>Great, big, expanded patio out back for social distanced dining. Weve enjoyed take out and outdoor dining in the past few months and this remains one of our favorite local restaurants. Their service continues to be top notch.

I have literally had everything on the menu, but the best still remains the blackened ahi sandwich with side arugula salad. My wife swears by the vegetarian big sur burger. <rate>5< /rate>< text>
This is a fantastic place to grab a bite eat or grab a drink.  This is the most happening place and on this side of Monterey.  So be prepared for a wait.  They have a large menu with plenty of great selections.  I had the Jerk Pork Plate.  It was properly spicy and tasted great.  The hamburger was a bit disappointing but this is not really a place to come for a burger.  They have a large number of tropical and traditional drinks.<//text>

<pics>None</pics><name>JOHN HAEUPTLE< /name><gmapID>0x808de6a9df290119:0x904f306efa704198</gmapID>< text>
It is a great get a away for the kids. Need some peace to be able to hear your own thoughts?  Want to put them to bed tired and willing?  This park has every conceivable contraption, swing, slide, and activity for them to let off all that pent up energy. It is very busy during the day, so go early.  There are tables to sit at and great spaces for parents to watch on the side without having to be in the thick of it. Most of the activities have plenty of room, so there is not a whole lot of waiting. So go take a break and be your kids' hero by giving them a whole lot to do very no money down.< /text>

This fun little Hawaiian grill in Monterey can make me feel like I'm back in Honolulu.  I ordered Duke's luau platter,  which did make me fondly remember the luau at the Hale Koa. The only thing missing was poi. The pulled pork and pineapple was great!

<text>It's rare that I'm at a loss for words, but this wonderful restaurant has absolutely blown me away. The food was so exquisite that we even decided to spend the second evening of our short stay with these lovely people.

< review>
This place is elegant as well as classy. Can be visited by family and friends but they are totally no no about the kids. They have a philosophy that leads to a serene environment. They totally want to avoid crying toddlers. I really liked that. Most of the time when toddlers cry its kinda never ending. Food and decor are fabulous and they have ample of parking area. The server was helpful and friendly, kept the drinks filled - and remembered what they were - and checked on us several times. We didn't feel neglected for not ordering alcohol, as is so often the case. She suggested a dessert she wasn't sure we'd like and she clapped and got excited when we loved it. Three different people thanked us for coming in. We have rarely felt so appreciated and attended at a restaurant. And the food was 5 stars also...</review><pictures>None< /pictures><resp>None< /resp>< GmapID>

<user>110748059180080444957</user>< name>
g v< /name>
<Time>1567711837569< /Time>< Rating>
5</Rating>
< Text>
I do not give a 5 star rating often. Hula's is an approachable understated exceptionally fun and flavorful experience. Immediately greeted by Lynnette my wife and I were seated by the window allowing us to see all the excitement of the bar and the servers. We arrived for happy hour and were encouraged to order off that menu. Everything is $6 and the flavors will blow your mind. Had seared ahi tuna, kona wings, abalone calamari and grilled avocado. All were bursting with unique flavors and left me wanting to try another dish. Drinks were spot on, not to light and fantastically balanced. Amazingly none of the cocktails were too sweet, all made with natural fruit juices and allowed to impart genuine flavors of the tropics. The atmosphere was relaxed and fun and the server made us feel welcome and appreciated; even making suggestions and listening to my gluten free rant. I do not get to Monterey often but when I do, Hula's is the place for me. KUDOS HULA'S!< /Text>

<Rate>4< /Rate>< Review>
4 stars because it is fun and has great staff. Excellent Hawaiian cocktails (favorite was the Painkiller) perfectly prepared and happy hour pricing is very reasonable.
Not 5 stars because they really glop on some of the sauces on the fish. Highly recommend getting the fish sauces on the side. Some of the sauces are just ok and really kill the dish if they are slathered on top of everything. However, this is easy to avoid so 4 stars.</Review>

ahi tacos, spicy, crispy, big portion. Amazing
Jawaiian jerk pork platter, spicy and AMAZING
Godzilla tots. Try them
Curry tofu bowl, so so good
Jawaiian chicken plate, also amazing.
Steak sandwich: this will change your life

Tasty drinks also.

< text>
This place is absolutely fantastic. The service is friendly and attentive, the drinks are well made and well priced (especially during happy hour) and the food is absolutely delicious. Dan, who had served some members of our party before, made the experience all the better with a lively and welcoming attitude - major shout out and gratitude for him. The vegan/vegetarian and gluten free options were a big hit with our V-GF group member, and the cajun burger I had was one of the best burgers I've had in my life. Never visit Monterey without stopping at Hula's - you won't regret it.</text>

<review>We were very excited to visit this restaurant for the name alone. They don't take reservations. They were very full but seated us with almost no wait. the decor is very cute and tropical kitschy. Our waitress  was snooty , unfriendly and had a blank stare the few times she actually came to our table. We ordered drinks and appetizers first.  Our drinks came but the appetizers never showed up. When they served our entrees the server tried to remove the dishes meant for our appetizers. When I mention we still had not received the appetizers,  the server walked away. A little while later another guy came to remove the appetizer plates again. This time I sarcastically mentioned that we never received our appetizers .  He then suggested to cancel our appetizers. At that point I was very irritated due to the service and the people next to us, so I said that he should just do what he thought was best for us. A little while after that our waitress finally returned to our table and said she put in the order for appetizers.  They eventually showed up after our meal was finished. No apologies although they did comp the appetizers .

FYI, the seating is very close together so the conversation at the next table will become your conversation, whether you want it to or not. Be forewarn. Once we were seated another group of four women were seated at the table next to us. They were ear piercingly loud and their entire conversation for over an hour consisted of dildos, vibrators, masturbation, and how to avoid having to give it to their husbands or how to get it from strangers without obligation. The food here must have been designed by an artist who sees protein as their canvas and complementary herbal matrimonies as their pallette. Sounds cheesy, but it‚Äôs true. The dishes are great! On top of that, our waitress (cute short-haired blonde lady on a Monday) was so passionate about the food and our satisfaction that I would have left happy even if my meal tasted terrible. Luckily it didn‚Äôt though.

< Review>
Tiki bar style at its finest. Suberb food selection that I can best describe as Asian/Hawaiian/Traditional American all molded into this delicious array of food options. The cocktails are great too (try the Zombie and make it a double!), with a laxed patio area for those warm sunny days, although they do have heaters for those chilly days and nights. If you're looking for something beyond the standard Monterey tourist sand dab and clam chowder options, then definitely check this place out!< /Review>

< Review>
Love Duke's Kalua Pork. I always order it with the fried plantains. Scrumptious. And the best mai tai I've ever had!  Fabulous food, friendly staff, awesome decor filled with vintage Hawaiiana that makes you feel as if you're in the islands. (Note: if it's a super hot day - -  which is rare for Monterey - - be warned that there is NO air conditioning. Plenty of fans, though.) Quaint outside patio.  A MUST if you're in Monterey or in Santa Cruz.  Hula's, please open in Santa Barbara!</Review>

< Text>
(Translated by Google) Fortunately, there is Google Maps. We didn't want to eat in the hustle and bustle of Cannery Row and looked for something with a good vegetarian selection and then found this great place.
Super friendly service, quick, attentive and helpful. Very good cocktails and incredibly delicious starters (tip: spicy Edamame & Coconut Shrimp Rolls). And at a happy hour price
The Caesars salad unfortunately lacked some sauce and the vegetarian bowl was also a bit dry. Still a visit.
